[The term "vertigins" was used and one person communicated that this term is
unsettling to him. He suspects this term should be used with only three
foodborne illnesses: botulism, trichinosis and cysticercosis. Assuming the
incubation period is short, then mild botulism might be something to
consider. Abramo Ottolenghi says the word "vertigine" in non-medical Italian
can simply mean dizziness. Clearly there is a very unclear etiology. These
are the sorts of reports that make ProMED-mail difficult (and even annoying)
to read at times. I posted this in spite of suhc risk because it is unlikely
that an "emerging" disease would have the characteristics of the common cold.
However, this and preceding reports on this subject (whatever the subject is)
are instructive in showing that definitive epidemiologic investigations are
an absolute necessity and that opinions, single-case reports, and media
speculations are not at all useful. If you are about to send a message to
ProMED-mail letting us know that this series of reports was not at all
"information", consider the we had to edit all this stuff. Provisional end
of string. -- Mod CHC]
